window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Chemistry Practical>2014>1>a","subject":"Chemistry Practical","year":"2014","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"ACIDS, BASES AND SALTS : ACID-BASE TITRATION","question":"Burette readings (initial and final) must be given to two decimal places. Volume of pipette used must also be recorded but no account of experimental procedure is required. All calculations must be done in your answer book.    A is a solution of hydrochloric acid. B is a solution containing 2.45g of anhydrous sodium trioxocarbonate (IV) in 250cm3 of solution.    Put A into the burette and titrate it against 20.0 cm3 or 25.0 cm3 portion of B using methyl orange as an indicator. Repeat the exercise to obtain consistent titres. Tabulate your burette reading and calculate the average volume of A used.   The equation for the reaction involved in the titration is Na2CO3(aq) + 2HCI(aq) \u2192 2NaCl(aq) + H2O(l) + CO2(g)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Burette Reading (cm3,Rough Titre,1st Titre,2nd Titre  Final Burette Reading (cm3)25.0048.5023.50Initial Burette Reading (cm3)0.0025.000.00Vol. of Acid Used (cm3)25.0023.5023.50  Average Vol. of Acid Used = (23.50 +23.50)/2  =23.50cm3","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Chemistry Practical>2014>1>b>i","subject":"Chemistry Practical","year":"2014","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"ACIDS, BASES AND SALTS : ACIDS","question":"From your results and the information provided, calculate the:    concentration of B in moldm\u22123","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Na2CO3(aq) + 2HCI(aq) \u2192 2NaCl(aq) + H2O(l) + CO2(g)  Molar mass (Na2CO3) = (2 x 23) + 12 + (3 x 15) = 106gmol\u22121    250cm3 of solution contained 2.45g of Na2CO3  1000cm3 of solution contained = 2.45\u00d71000/250  = 2.45 x 4   = 9.80g   Con. B (Na2CO3) = 9.80/106  = 0.0925 mol dm\u22123","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Chemistry Practical>2014>1>b>ii","subject":"Chemistry Practical","year":"2014","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"ACIDS, BASES AND SALTS : ACIDS","question":"From your results and the information provided, calculate the:  concentration of A in moldm\u22123","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Concentration of A in moldm\u22123  CAVA/CBVB=nA/nB  CA=? VA=23.50, nB=2, CB = 0.092mol/dm3, VB=25cm3, nA=1  CA=CBVBnA/VAnB  =0.0925 x 25.00 x 2/23.50 x 1  =0.197 moldm-3","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Chemistry Practical>2014>1>b>iii","subject":"Chemistry Practical","year":"2014","type":"Practical","sub_label":"iii","group":"","topic":"ACIDS, BASES AND SALTS : ACIDS","question":"From your results and the information provided, calculate the:  concentration of A in gdm\u22123","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Concentration of A in gdm\u22123  Molar mass HCl = 1 + 35.5 = 36.5  Conc of A(gdm\u22123) = 0.197 x 36.5  = 7.19 gdm\u22123","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Chemistry Practical>2014>1>b>iv","subject":"Chemistry Practical","year":"2014","type":"Practical","sub_label":"iv","group":"","topic":"ACIDS, BASES AND SALTS : ACID-BASE REACTIONS","question":"From your results and the information provided, calculate the:  volume of the gas evolved in the reaction at s.t.p.  [H = 1.00; C=12.0; O = 16.0;  Na= 23.0; Cl = 35.5; Molar Volume = 22.4dm3 mol\u22123]","images":[],"marking_scheme":"1 mole of Na2CO3 = 1 mole of CO2 at s.t.p     n(CO2) = n(Na2CO3 =0.0925mole   vol. of CO2 = n x volume   = 0.0925 x 22.4 dm\u22123  = 2.07dm3 at s.t.p  Volume of CO2 liberated in 25 cm3 of Na2CO3 will be 2.07\u00d7 25/1000  = 0.0518 dm3 or 51.8 cm3 at s.t.p","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Chemistry Practical>2014>2","subject":"Chemistry Practical","year":"2014","type":"Practical","sub_label":"2","group":"","topic":"ACIDS, BASES AND SALTS : ACID-BASE REACTIONS","question":"Credit will be given for strict adherence to the instructions, for observations, precisely recorded, and for accurate inferences. All tests, observations, and inferences must be clearly entered in your answer book, in ink, at the time they are made.  C contains two cations and two anions. Perform the following exercises on C. Record your observations and identify any gas(es) evolved. State the conclusion you draw from the result of each test.  (a) Dissolve all of C in about 10 cm3 of distilled water. Stir the resulting solution thoroughly.  (i) To about 2 cm3 of the solution, add few drops of AgNO3 solution, followed by HNO3(aq). To the mixture, add excess NH3(aq)  (ii) To another 2 cm3 portion of the solution, add dil. HCl followed by BaCl2 solution.  (iii) To another 2 cm3 portion of the solution, add NaOH(aq) dropwise and then in excess. Warm the mixture.  (iv) To another 2 cm3  portion of the solution, add NH3(aq) dropwise and then in excess.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"TESTOBSERVATIONINFERENCEa(i) C(aq) + AgNO3 + HNO3(aq) + NH3(aq) excessWhite precipitate formed. precipitate insoluble. Precipitate soluble/dissolved Cl-; S2-; CO32- indicated. Cl- present(ii) C(aq) + HCl(aq) + BaCl2(aq)No visible reaction/no gas evolved. White (chalky) precipitate formed SO42-(iii) C(aq) + NaOH(aq) in drops; in excess; Mixture warmedWhite gelatinous precipitate. White precipitate dissolved/soluble. Colourless gas evolved pungent/choking/irritating smell evolved. Gas turns red litmus paper blue or forms dense white fumes with conc. HCl Zn2+; Al3+ indicated; Zn2+; Al3+ indicated; NH3 gas evolved; NH4+ present  (iv) C(aq) + NH3(aq) in drops; in excess White gelatinous precipitate; Precipitate dissolved/solubleZn2+; Al3+ indicated. Zn2+ present.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Chemistry Practical>2014>3>i","subject":"Chemistry Practical","year":"2014","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"STATES OF MATTER : LABORATORY PREPARATION AND PROPERTIES OF SOME GASES.","question":"Consider the following experimental set-up.      Identify by name: P; Q; R; S and T.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"P - Delivery tube  Q - Drying tower  R - Calcium oxide   S - Ammonia gas   T - Retort stand with clamp","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Chemistry Practical>2014>3>ii","subject":"Chemistry Practical","year":"2014","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"STATES OF MATTER : LABORATORY PREPARATION AND PROPERTIES OF SOME GASES.","question":"Consider the following experimental set-up.    State the method of collection of gas, S.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Upward delivery of gas/downward displacement of air","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Chemistry Practical>2014>3>iii","subject":"Chemistry Practical","year":"2014","type":"Practical","sub_label":"iii","group":"","topic":"STATES OF MATTER : LABORATORY PREPARATION AND PROPERTIES OF SOME GASES.","question":"Consider the following experimental set-up.    What is the function of R in the experimental set-up?","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"To dry the gas","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Chemistry Practical>2014>3>iv","subject":"Chemistry Practical","year":"2014","type":"Practical","sub_label":"iv","group":"","topic":"ACIDS, BASES AND SALTS : ACID-BASE REACTIONS","question":"Consider the following experimental set-up.    Write the balanced equation of the reaction for the preparation of gas S.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Ca(OH)2(aq) + 2NH4Cl(aq) \u2192 CaCl2(aq) + 2H2O(l) + 2NH3(g)","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"}];